solution:
In a conductor, \(\boldsymbol{j} = \sigma \boldsymbol{E}, \rho = 0\), so the Maxwell's equations are

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \nabla \times \boldsymbol{E} = -\frac{\partial \boldsymbol{B}}{\partial t}, \quad \nabla \times \boldsymbol{H} = \frac{\partial \boldsymbol{D}}{\partial t} + \boldsymbol{j} \\
& \nabla \cdot \boldsymbol{D} = \nabla \cdot \boldsymbol{B} = 0 \\
& \boldsymbol{D} = \varepsilon \boldsymbol{E}, \quad \boldsymbol{B} = \mu \boldsymbol{H}
\end{aligned}
$$

For steady-state electromagnetic waves

$$
\boldsymbol{E}(\boldsymbol{x}, t) = \boldsymbol{E}(\boldsymbol{x}) e^{-i \omega t}, \quad \boldsymbol{B}(\boldsymbol{x}, t) = \boldsymbol{B}(\boldsymbol{x}) e^{-i \omega t}
$$

From Maxwell's equations, we obtain

\begin{gather*}
\left\{
\begin{array}{l}
\nabla \times \boldsymbol{E}(\boldsymbol{x}) = i \omega \mu \boldsymbol{H}(\boldsymbol{x}) \\
\nabla \times \boldsymbol{H}(\boldsymbol{x}) = -i \omega \varepsilon \boldsymbol{E}(\boldsymbol{x}) + \sigma \boldsymbol{E}(\boldsymbol{x}) \\
\nabla \cdot \boldsymbol{E}(\boldsymbol{x}) = \nabla \cdot \boldsymbol{B}(\boldsymbol{x}) = 0
\end{array}
\right.  \tag{1}\\
\begin{aligned}
\nabla \times (\nabla \times \boldsymbol{E}) = \nabla (\nabla \cdot \boldsymbol{E}) - \nabla^2 \boldsymbol{E} = -\nabla^2 \boldsymbol{E} \\
= i \omega \mu \nabla \times \boldsymbol{H} = (\omega^2 \varepsilon \mu + i \omega \mu \sigma) \boldsymbol{E}
\end{aligned}
\end{gather*}

Let

\begin{equation*}
k^{\prime 2} = \omega^2 \mu \varepsilon^{\prime}, \quad \varepsilon^{\prime} = \varepsilon + i \frac{\sigma}{\omega} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}

Then

\begin{equation*}
\nabla^2 \boldsymbol{E}(\boldsymbol{x}) + k^{\prime 2} \boldsymbol{E}(\boldsymbol{x}) = 0 \tag{3}
\end{equation*}

This is the Helmholtz equation, and a plane wave is one of its solutions:

$$
\boldsymbol{E}(\boldsymbol{x}) = \boldsymbol{E}_{0} e^{i \boldsymbol{k}^{\prime} \cdot \boldsymbol{x}}
$$

where \(\boldsymbol{k}^{\prime}\) is the complex wave vector. Let \(\boldsymbol{k}^{\prime} = \boldsymbol{\beta} + i \boldsymbol{\alpha}\), then

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \beta^2 - \alpha^2 = \omega^2 \mu \varepsilon \\
& \boldsymbol{\beta} \cdot \boldsymbol{\alpha} = \frac{1}{2} \omega \mu \sigma
\end{aligned}
$$

For the problem, the incident wave \( E = E_{y0} e^{i(kz - \omega t)} \), and

$$
\boldsymbol{k} = k \boldsymbol{e}_{z}, \quad \boldsymbol{E}_{0} = \boldsymbol{E}_{y0} \boldsymbol{e}_{y}, \quad \boldsymbol{B}_{0} = \boldsymbol{B}_{x0} \boldsymbol{e}_{x}
$$

Assume the transmitted wave in the semi-infinite medium is \(\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime \prime}, \boldsymbol{B}^{\prime \prime}\), then

$$
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime \prime} = \boldsymbol{E}_{0}^{\prime \prime} e^{i(k^{\prime} \cdot z - \omega t)}, \quad \boldsymbol{B}^{\prime \prime} = \boldsymbol{B}_{0}^{\prime \prime} e^{i(k^{\prime} \cdot z - \omega t)}
\end{aligned}
$$

At the boundary, to ensure boundary conditions apply at every point on the surface, we must have

$$
\boldsymbol{k} \cdot \boldsymbol{x} = \left.\boldsymbol{k}^{\prime} \cdot \boldsymbol{x}\right|_{z=0}
$$

From which we deduce

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \alpha_{x} = \alpha_{y} = \beta_{x} = \beta_{y} = 0 \\
& \boldsymbol{k}^{\prime} = k^{\prime} \boldsymbol{e}_{z} \\
& k^{\prime} = \beta + i \alpha
\end{aligned}
$$

The \(\beta\), \(\alpha\) satisfy the set of equations

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \beta^2 - \alpha^2 = \omega^2 \mu \varepsilon \\
& \beta \alpha = \frac{1}{2} \omega \mu \sigma
\end{aligned}
$$

The solutions are

\begin{align*}
& \beta = \omega \sqrt{\mu \varepsilon} \left[\frac{1}{2} \left( 1 + \sqrt{1 + \frac{\sigma^2}{\varepsilon^2 \omega^2}} \right)\right]^{1/2}  \tag{4}\\
& \alpha = \omega \sqrt{\mu \varepsilon} \left[\frac{1}{2} \left(-1 + \sqrt{1 + \frac{\sigma^2}{\varepsilon^2 \omega^2}} \right)\right]^{1/2} \tag{5}
\end{align*}

Next, use boundary conditions to find the amplitude of the transmitted wave. Let the amplitude of the reflected wave be \(\boldsymbol{E}_{0}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{H}_{0}^{\prime}\). Due to the transverse nature of plane waves and the continuity of the normal component of \(\boldsymbol{E}\) and the tangential component of \(\boldsymbol{H}\) at the boundary, one deduces that the electric field of the reflected and refracted waves only has a \(y\) component, and the magnetic field only has an \(x\) component, satisfying

\begin{align*}
& E_{y0} + E_{y0}^{\prime} = E_{y0}^{\prime \prime}  \tag{6}\\
& E_{x0} + E_{x0}^{\prime} = E_{x0}^{\prime \prime} \tag{7}
\end{align*}

For the incident and reflected waves, \(H_{x0} = \sqrt{\frac{\varepsilon_{0}}{\mu_{0}}} E_{y0}, H_{x0}^{\prime} = \sqrt{\frac{\varepsilon_{0}}{\mu_{0}}} E_{y0}^{\prime}\). From equation (1), \(H_{x0}^{\prime \prime} = \frac{k^{\prime}}{\omega \mu} E_{y0}^{\prime \prime}\), thus equation (7) becomes

\begin{equation*}
\sqrt{\frac{\varepsilon_{0}}{\mu_{0}}}(E_{y0} - E_{y0}^{\prime}) = \frac{k^{\prime}}{\omega \mu} E_{y0}^{\prime \prime} \tag{8}
\end{equation*}

Solving equations (6) and (8) together gives

\begin{equation*}
E_{y0}^{\prime \prime} = \frac{2 E_{y0}}{1 + \sqrt{\frac{\mu_{0}}{\varepsilon_{0}}} \cdot \frac{k^{\prime}}{\omega \mu}} \tag{9}
\end{equation*}

When \(\sigma\) is large and real, and \(\omega\) is low frequency, we have

$$
\frac{\sigma}{\varepsilon \omega} \gg 1, \quad \sqrt{1 + \frac{\sigma^2}{\varepsilon^2 \omega^2}} \pm 1 \approx \frac{\sigma}{\varepsilon \omega}
$$

Thus

\begin{equation*}
\beta = \alpha \approx \sqrt{\frac{\omega \mu \sigma}{2}} \tag{10}
\end{equation*}

Therefore,

\begin{align*}
& k^{\prime} = \sqrt{\frac{\omega \mu \sigma}{2}}(1+i) \\
& E_{y0}^{\prime \prime} = \frac{2 E_{y0}}{\left(1 + \sqrt{\frac{\mu_{0} \sigma}{2 \varepsilon_{0} \omega \mu}} + i \sqrt{\frac{\mu_{0} \sigma}{2 \varepsilon_{0} \omega \mu}}\right)} \tag{11}
\end{align*}

The electric field in the metal is therefore

\begin{equation*}
E^{\prime \prime} = E_{y0}^{\prime \prime} e^{-\alpha z} e^{i(\beta z - \omega t)} e_{y} \tag{12}
\end{equation*}

From the problem statement, we obtain the expressions for $\boldsymbol{B}$ and $\boldsymbol{E}$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \boldsymbol{B}=\nabla \times \boldsymbol{A}=i \boldsymbol{k} \times \boldsymbol{A}_{0} e^{i(\boldsymbol{k} \cdot \boldsymbol{x}-\omega t)} \\
& \boldsymbol{E}=-\frac{\partial \boldsymbol{A}}{\partial t}=i \omega \boldsymbol{A}_{0} e^{i(\boldsymbol{k} \cdot \boldsymbol{x}-\omega t)}
\end{aligned}
$$

