(c) The spatial reflection transformation is given by

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\boldsymbol{r} \rightarrow \boldsymbol{r}^{\prime} = -\boldsymbol{r}, & \nabla \rightarrow \nabla^{\prime} = -\nabla \\
\frac{\partial}{\partial t} \rightarrow \frac{\partial}{\partial t^{\prime}}, & e \rightarrow e^{\prime} = e
\end{array}
$$

It is clear that in this case we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \rho(\boldsymbol{r}, t) \rightarrow \rho^{\prime}(\boldsymbol{r}, t) = \rho, \\
& \boldsymbol{j} \rightarrow \boldsymbol{j}^{\prime} = -\boldsymbol{j}
\end{aligned}
$$

By applying the law of charge conservation and rewriting the unaltered Maxwell's equations after the transformation, similar to approach (b), it can be proven that

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \boldsymbol{E}^{\prime}(\boldsymbol{r}, t) = -\boldsymbol{E}(\boldsymbol{r}, t), \\
& \boldsymbol{B}^{\prime}(\boldsymbol{r}, t) = \boldsymbol{B}(\boldsymbol{r}, t)
\end{aligned}
$$

Let the displacement of the charged particle in a time $\mathrm{d} t$ be $\mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{x}$, then the increment in the vector potential $\boldsymbol{A}$ is $(\mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{x} \cdot \nabla) \boldsymbol{A}$. Therefore, the rate of change of $\boldsymbol{A}$ is

\begin{equation*}
\frac{\mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{A}}{\mathrm{~d} t}=\frac{\partial \boldsymbol{A}}{\partial t}+(\boldsymbol{v} \cdot \nabla) \boldsymbol{A} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}

In an electromagnetic field, the equation of motion for a charged particle with momentum $\boldsymbol{P}$ is

\begin{equation*}
\frac{\mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{P}}{\mathrm{~d} t}=e(\boldsymbol{E}+ \boldsymbol{v} \times \boldsymbol{B}) \tag{2}
\end{equation*}

Note that in the Lagrangian formulation, $x$ and $\boldsymbol{v}$ are independent variables, thus

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{v} \times (\nabla \times \boldsymbol{A})=\nabla(\boldsymbol{v} \cdot \boldsymbol{A})-(\boldsymbol{v} \cdot \nabla) \boldsymbol{A} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}

Substitute equation (3) into equation (2), and given $\varphi=0$, we get

\begin{equation*}
\frac{\mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{P}}{\mathrm{~d} t}=e \nabla(\boldsymbol{v} \cdot \boldsymbol{A})-e \frac{\mathrm{~d} \boldsymbol{A}}{\mathrm{~d} t} \tag{4}
\end{equation*}

For the plane electromagnetic wave in this problem, the vector potential $\boldsymbol{A}(x-ct)$ is independent of coordinates $y$ and $z$, so $\nabla(\boldsymbol{v} \cdot \boldsymbol{A})$ has no transverse component. For the transverse component $\boldsymbol{P}_{\perp}=P_{y} \boldsymbol{e}_{y}+P_{z} \boldsymbol{e}_{z}$, the equation of motion is

\begin{equation*}
\frac{\mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{P}_{\perp}}{\mathrm{d} t}=-e \frac{\mathrm{~d} \boldsymbol{A}_{\perp}}{\mathrm{d} t} \tag{5}
\end{equation*}

Integrating equation (5) yields

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{P}_{\perp}=-e \boldsymbol{A}_{\perp}+C \tag{6}
\end{equation*}

Since the initial speed of the particle is 0, the constant $C$ equals zero. Furthermore, given that $A_{z}=0$, $\boldsymbol{A}_{\perp}=\boldsymbol{A}$. Therefore, we finally obtain

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{P}_{\perp}=-e \boldsymbol{A} \tag{7}
\end{equation*}

