we know that the requirement is

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{B} = \frac{\boldsymbol{v}}{c^{2}} \times \boldsymbol{E}
\end{equation*}

Furthermore, from

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{E} \times \boldsymbol{B} = \frac{1}{c^{2}} \boldsymbol{E} \times (\boldsymbol{v} \times \boldsymbol{E}) = \frac{E^{2}}{c^{2}} \boldsymbol{v}
\end{equation*}

it can be seen that by choosing $\boldsymbol{v} = \frac{c^{2}}{E^{2}} \boldsymbol{E} \times \boldsymbol{B}$, we can make $\boldsymbol{B}^{\prime} = 0$. The electric field is then

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} = \gamma(\boldsymbol{E} + \boldsymbol{v} \times \boldsymbol{B}) = \gamma\left(1 - \frac{c^{2} B^{2}}{E^{2}}\right) \boldsymbol{E} = \frac{\boldsymbol{E}}{\gamma} \neq 0
\end{equation*}

Additionally,

\begin{equation*}
\frac{1}{\gamma^{2}} = 1 - \frac{v^{2}}{c^{2}} = 1 - \frac{c^{2} B^{2}}{E^{2}}>0
\end{equation*}

To summarize, when $E^{2} > c^{2} B^{2}$ and $\boldsymbol{v} = \frac{c^{2}}{E^{2}}(\boldsymbol{E} \times \boldsymbol{B})$ is chosen, $\boldsymbol{B}^{\prime} = 0$ and $\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} \neq 0$.

According to the problem, in the laboratory frame $\Sigma$, the charge density of the beam is $\rho$. Due to the Lorentz longitudinal contraction effect, in the rest frame of the beam $\Sigma^{\prime}$, the charge density is $\rho / \gamma (\gamma = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 - v^{2}/c^{2}}})$. In the $\Sigma^{\prime}$ frame, $\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} = \frac{\rho r^{\prime}}{2 \varepsilon_{0} \gamma} \boldsymbol{e}_{r}, \boldsymbol{B}^{\prime} = 0$. In the laboratory frame $\Sigma$, with $v = v e_{z}$, we have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \boldsymbol{E}_{\perp} = \gamma (\boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} - v \times \boldsymbol{B})_{\perp} = \gamma \boldsymbol{E}^{\prime}, \quad \boldsymbol{E}_{\parallel} = \boldsymbol{E}_{\parallel}^{\prime} = 0 \\
& \boldsymbol{B}_{\perp} = \gamma (\boldsymbol{B}^{\prime} + \frac{v}{c^{2}} \times \boldsymbol{E}^{\prime})_{\perp} = \gamma \frac{v}{c^{2}} \times \boldsymbol{E}^{\prime}, \quad \boldsymbol{B}_{\parallel} = \boldsymbol{B}_{\parallel}^{\prime} = 0
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the force experienced by the electron is:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{F} & = -e \boldsymbol{E} - e v \times \boldsymbol{B} = -e \cdot \gamma \boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} - e v \times \left(\gamma \frac{v}{c^{2}} \times \boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} \right) \\
& = -e \gamma \boldsymbol{E}^{\prime} + e \gamma \frac{v^{2}}{c^{2}} \boldsymbol{E}^{\prime}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since there is no transverse Lorentz contraction, $r = r^{\prime}$, thus:

$$
\boldsymbol{F} = -\frac{e \boldsymbol{E}^{\prime}}{\gamma} = -\frac{e \rho r}{2 \varepsilon_{0} \gamma^{2}} \boldsymbol{e}_{r}
$$

