The Maxwell's equations in the context of the medium are

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \nabla \cdot \boldsymbol{D}=0, \quad \nabla \cdot \boldsymbol{B}=0 \\
& \nabla \times \boldsymbol{E}=-\frac{\partial \boldsymbol{B}}{\partial t}, \quad \nabla \times \boldsymbol{H}=\boldsymbol{J}+\frac{\partial \boldsymbol{D}}{\partial t}
\end{aligned}
$$

Note that the fields $\boldsymbol{E}$, $\boldsymbol{B}$ here are superpositions of the external fields and the fields generated by the time-varying magnetization intensity $\boldsymbol{M}(t)$, meaning they already include the fields produced by $\boldsymbol{M}(t)$.

Since it is an insulating medium and assuming the medium cannot carry charge, we have $\rho=0, \quad \boldsymbol{J}=0$. Given that $\varepsilon_{r}=1$, it follows that $\boldsymbol{D}=\varepsilon_{0} \boldsymbol{E}$. Therefore, the equations simplify to

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \nabla \cdot \boldsymbol{E}=0, \quad \nabla \cdot \boldsymbol{B}=0 \\
& \nabla \times \boldsymbol{E}=-\frac{\partial \boldsymbol{B}}{\partial t}, \quad \nabla \times \boldsymbol{H}=\varepsilon_{0} \frac{\partial \boldsymbol{E}}{\partial t}, \quad \boldsymbol{B}=\mu \boldsymbol{H}
\end{aligned}
$$

From this, the wave equations are derived as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \nabla^{2} \boldsymbol{E}-\mu \varepsilon_{0} \frac{\partial^{2} \boldsymbol{E}}{\partial t^{2}}=0 \\
& \nabla^{2} \boldsymbol{H}-\mu \varepsilon_{0} \frac{\partial^{2} \boldsymbol{H}}{\partial t^{2}}=0
\end{aligned}
$$

A plane wave solution to these equations is

$$
\boldsymbol{H}(t)=\boldsymbol{H}_{0} e^{i(kz-\omega t)}
$$

Substituting this into the wave equation, the dispersion relation can be obtained as

$$
k^{2}-\mu \varepsilon_{0} \omega^{2}=0, \quad k^{2}=\frac{\omega}{v_{p}}=\omega \sqrt{\mu(\omega) \varepsilon_{0}}=\frac{\omega}{c} \sqrt{\mu(\omega)}
$$

The magnetization intensity plane wave in the medium is

$$
\boldsymbol{M}(t)=\chi_{m}(\omega) \boldsymbol{H}(t)=\chi_{m} \boldsymbol{H}_{0} e^{i(kz-\omega t)}
$$

Thus, the dispersion relation for this plane wave remains

$$
k^{2}=\frac{\omega}{v_{p}}=\frac{\omega}{c} \sqrt{\mu(\omega)}
$$

